President Obama announced the recipients of the 2009 Presidential Medal of Freedom, America's highest civilian honor. The medal is awarded to individuals who have made significant contributions to the security or national interests of the United States, world peace, cultural or other significant public or private endeavors. This year's recipients were chosen for their work as agents of change, and they have made a positive impact in various fields such as sports, art, science, medicine, politics, and public policy. The 16 recipients include Nancy Goodman Brinker, Pedro José Greer Jr., Stephen Hawking, Jack Kemp, Sen. Edward Kennedy, Billie Jean King, Rev. Joseph Lowery, Joe Medicine Crow – High Bird, Harvey Milk, Sandra Day O'Connor, Sidney Poitier, Chita Rivera, Mary Robinson, Janet Davison Rowley, Desmond Tutu, and Muhammad Yunus. These individuals have blazed trails, broken down barriers, and improved the world in their respective fields. They will be awarded the Medal of Freedom at a ceremony on August 12, 2009.